<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>. . . daughter/wife] of Hypsikles [ . . . </p>
</div>
<div type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>One of the series of dedications from the East Court of the Hadrianic Baths: <xref type="iAph">1184</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1186</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1187</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1188</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1189</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1190</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1191</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1192</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1193</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1194</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1195</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1196</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1197</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1198</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1199</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1200</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1201</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1202</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1203</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1204</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1205</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1206</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1208</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1209</xref>, <xref type="iAph">1210</xref> ; all are by women, and apparently bore caryatids (see <xref type="iAph">1198</xref>).</p><p>Boulanger suggests that this is from the same base as XXX Portico 4, with which it was found.</p>
</div>
